    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Marketplace Tampering</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Sheldon Richman letter responds to Asst Atty Gen Joel I Klein's June 13 Op-Ed article on Microsoft antitrust case; warns government's own actions may stifle, not promote, innovation and competition</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Joel I. Klein's June 13 Op-Ed article about Microsoft beautifully illustrates the principle that government intervention in the marketplace has unseen, unintended consequences. If the government in effect compels a new Microsoft applications company to cater to users of the Palm Pilot and Linux, other entrepreneurs may be discouraged from filling those market niches with new, perhaps better products.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Joel I. Klein's June 13 Op-Ed article about Microsoft beautifully illustrates the principle that government intervention in the marketplace has unseen, unintended consequences. If the government in effect compels a new Microsoft applications company to cater to users of the Palm Pilot and Linux, other entrepreneurs may be discouraged from filling those market niches with new, perhaps better products.</p>
        <p>Thus, according to Mr. Klein's theory, innovation and competition will be stifled by the government's own actions. Wherever the Justice Department squeezes the balloon, the air will bulge out somewhere else.</p>
        <p>SHELDON RICHMAN  Irvington, N.Y., June 13, 2000</p>
        <p>The writer is editor of the monthly magazine of the Foundation for Economic Education.</p>
      </block>
